Six months into joining NBFC, I inherited a 4,000-line TypeScript file named `api.service.ts`. It was a hand-written HTTP client that talked to about 40 backend endpoints. Every method looked like this:
getLoanApplicationById(id: string): Observable<any> {
return this.http.get<any>(`${this.baseUrl}/loans/${id}`);
}Three problems jumped out immediately. The return types were `any`. The request payloads had no type checking. And any time the backend team changed an API contract, someone had to remember to update this file — which they didn’t, consistently.
We had runtime errors catching contract changes that a TypeScript compiler should have caught at build time. We had frontend engineers spending hours writing service methods that could have been generated in seconds.
Here’s how I stopped that.
The Backend Was Already OpenAPI-Compliant
Our Spring Boot services exposed Swagger UI at `/v3/api-docs`. The JSON schema was sitting there the entire time, completely ignored by the frontend team. A typical endpoint schema fragment looked like this:
